/*******************************************************************************
    Incant bytecodes — structure, registries, and how the generator emits them.

    --------------------------------------------------------------------------
    1. What a bytecode IS

    A bytecode instruction is a GroupItem. (Same shape as everything else in
    incant — homoiconic at the bytecode layer, not just at the source layer.)

    Each instruction has:
        * a tag       — the opcode mnemonic (bcBR, bcPushLit, '>', '=', '*', ...)
        * operands    — named sub-attributes on the instruction. Conventional
                        slot names: op1, op2, cond, target, value, dst.
                        Bytecode.mm handlers read operands by name:
                            instr->getAttribute("op1")
        * interpret   — sub-attribute whose method is the C++ handler that
                        executes the op. Resolved at dispatch time by the
                        one-method-per-field rule:
                            handler = grup.interpret;
                            result  = handler(grup);

    The `interpret` sub-attribute is NOT stored on each emitted instance —
    it's inherited from the registry entry where the op was declared. Emitting
    an op by tag is enough; dispatch finds the handler via the registered
    template.

    Note vs. standard bytecodes: most VMs encode bytecodes as opaque
    tuples — an opcode byte followed by operand bytes, decoded by a
    switch in the interpreter. Incant bytecodes are GroupItems, the
    same data shape as source and as everything else in the language,
    so dispatch is attribute lookup rather than decoding, and the
    interpreter can be written in incant. incant's primary
    interpreter runs off the parse tree, not off bytecode; the bytecode
    layer is the IR the JIT will eventually compile, and exists today
    as an interpretable second path gated per-action by the bytecodE
    attribute.

    --------------------------------------------------------------------------
    2. Where bytecodes live (the registries)

    Bytecodes come from two registries today.

    (a) bcOPs (incant/setup) — control flow plus data-movement ops.
            bcBR         interpret=runBR
            bcBRZ        interpret=runBRZ
            bcCALL       interpret=runCall
            bcRET        interpret=runRET
            bcPushLit    interpret=runPushLit     (virtual)
            bcPushField  interpret=runPushField   (virtual)
            bcStoreField interpret=runStoreField
        Kept separate from Operators per the 2026-04-27 design decision: user
        code never writes bcBR, and an incant program walking Operators should
        not see them.

    (b) Operators (incant/setup) — user-facing operators that ALSO act
        as bytecode ops, via a second `interpret=` sub-attribute alongside the
        existing `operateMethod=`. Each shim is a runX in Bytecode.mm that
        wraps the corresponding opX. Today:
            '>'   operateMethod=opGT        interpret=runGT
            '='   operateMethod=opAssign    interpret=runAssign
            '*'   operateMethod=opMultiply  interpret=runMultiply
        Extending this set is a matter of (i) writing runX in Bytecode.mm,
        (ii) adding `interpret=runX` to the Operators entry. The op's tag is
        its symbol — that's what appears in the emitted instruction stream.

    (c) Resolved (2026-06-03): the data-movement ops bcPushLit, bcPushField
        and bcStoreField are now registered in bcOPs (setup:137-139) with
        handlers in Bytecode.twk (runPushLit, runPushField, runStoreField).
        bcMul was NOT added: multiply dispatches through the '*' operator
        (interpret=runMultiply in Operators, the shim pattern in (b)), so the
        emitter emits '*', never bcMul. (The stale testEmitBC fixture that still
        referenced bcMul was retired 2026-06-04 — Brief 5 Fix 3.)

    --------------------------------------------------------------------------
    3. The emit side — bcPushField and friends

    The call shape is:
        emitBC(bcPushField:=argument);

    Read this as: pass one operand to emitBC, whose tag is bcPushField and
    whose value is the source-tree GroupItem referenced by `argument`.
    Inside emitBC (actual, generate:296):
        :generator bcLIST;        // bind the accumulator off the generator
        bcLIST += argument;       // append the instruction as a member

    So `bcLIST` accumulates the emitted instruction stream for one action.
    Each emitBC() call adds one instruction. The instruction's tag IS the
    opcode; its payload (when present) IS the value of the field passed in.

    Multi-operand instructions are not expressed by the current single-operand
    emitBC shape — when those emerge (anything needing op1/op2/dst together),
    the emitter will need to build the instruction GroupItem with named
    sub-attributes filled in, then attach it. Forward-looking, not blocking.

    The members-vs-attributes note is STALE (corrected 2026-06-04, Brief 5):
    emitBC uses `+=` (opPlusEQ), not `+%`. On a list-typed target `+=` appends
    as a member, which is exactly what interpretBC's `for grup in body; members`
    walk needs. THE REAL BLOCKER is upstream: bcLIST is born via new("bcLIST")
    in generateCode (Commands.rtn:162) with NO data and NO groupList, so the
    first `+=` falls into opPlusEQ's copyData branch (Instruct.rtn:450) — it
    copies the first instruction's scalar data INTO bcLIST instead of appending,
    and every later `+=` does scalar arithmetic. bcLIST never becomes a list, so
    nothing accumulates as members and the copy-back to field.bcLIST (gated on
    accumulated.groupList, Commands.rtn:181) never fires. Fix: give bcLIST a
    groupList at creation so opPlusEQ takes the list-append branch (line 451).
    C++/.rtn change, rebuild-gated — Tony's seat. See TODO 2026-06-04.

    --------------------------------------------------------------------------
    4. Generating registry — how the pieces fit

    `Generating` is the registry this file defines. It holds:
        * types               — data → C++ type mapping (used by getType)
        * generateAction      — entry point: generates one action's code by
                                parsing it (generateCode), then either firing
                                interpret() over the resulting bytecode or
                                emitting C++ source directly
        * generateSignature   — C++ method signature emitter
        * runGenerated        — dispatcher. Looks up the per-tag generator
                                method by texT and invokes it on the argument.
                                Falls through to a literal print if no handler
                                exists for the tag.
        * generator           — hashed list of per-tag generator methods. Each
                                method handles one statement form:
                                    gBlocK, gDeclare, gDO, gExpressioN,
                                    gFOR, gIF, gPrinT, gWhilE, gXpress
                                These are reached via runGenerated, which is
                                the single point of dispatch over the parse
                                tree.
        * emitBC              — append-one-instruction primitive used by the
                                generator methods that produce bytecode (vs.
                                producing C++ text directly).
        * generatE            — top-level walk that calls runGenerated on each
                                top-level statement.

    The generator-methods-to-bytecode chain, in one breath:
        generateAction → generateCode → generatE → runGenerated → gXX → emitBC
                                                                       → bcLIST
        ...then interpret(bcLIST) walks bcLIST and dispatches each grup via
        its interpret sub-attribute to a Bytecode.mm handler.

    Two output modes co-exist in the same generator machinery: gBlocK / gFOR /
    gWhilE / gDO emit C++ source text via print; gIF / gExpressioN / gXpress
    emit bytecode via emitBC. Once Phase Bytecode is complete the text-emit
    paths get replaced (see jit.md). Until then, mixed output from one
    generateCode pass is expected.

*******************************************************************************/

/*******************************************************************************
	Types registry is a list of the types associated with field data. Referenced
    in getType(). Isn't it nice we can use quotes to define a field tag.
    Note: type tags use C++ syntax for pointer to type
*******************************************************************************/
register(Generating);
define
    types
        "Buffer*";
        int;
        char;
        "char*";
        "GroupItem*";
        GroupItem;
        "BitMAP*";
        double;
        "NSObject*";
        "PLGset*";
        "Stak*";
        "void*";
        void;
    startBlock='{';
    endBlock='}';
    asterisk='*';
    declareList sort;
    /***************************************************************************
        Generate action code.
    ***************************************************************************/
    generateAction action code={
        // generateCode parses the action to produce code to interpret
        generated = generateCode(action);
        //printTO(stringBUFFER);
        if generated;
            generateSignature(action);
            print _;
            //generated**;
            interpretBC(generated);
            //printTO(null);
        else print "generateCode failed":;
        };
    /***************************************************************************
        Generate C++ method signature.
    ***************************************************************************/
    generateSignature action code={
        //print "Generating signature for" tag:;
        print "GroupItem*",tag "(";
        for field in action; attributes
            if field.isArgument
                if follows;  print ",";
                print getType(field) taG;
                follows++;
        print ")";
        };
    /***************************************************************************
        generator is a hashed list of actions that process statements that
        generate (print) code. It is used in the generate() action below.
    ***************************************************************************/
    runGenerated argument code={
        print :"runGenerated: ";
        clear(action);
        **argument;
        if action := generator[argument];
            print "action is:" action.taG:;
            action(argument);
        else    print ~,argument ";":;
        print "End of runGenerated":; };
    generator
        gBlocK argument code={
            print "process block":;
            lines = argument[1];
            for grup in lines;
                runGenerated(grup);
            };
        gDeclare argument code={
            for field in argument; attributes
                if !isArgument
                    print "gDeclare: field and argument" taG argument.taG:;
                    if !isLocal AND !isArgument; print "GroupItem*" taG, "= locate(" taG ");":;
                    else    print  getType(field) ,taG ";":; };
        gDO argument code={
            //print "generate do":;
            st  = argument[1];
            xp  = argument[2];
            print ~"do"`;
            runGenerated(st);
            print ~,"while(" xp ");":; };
        gExpressioN argument code={
            print "Need to work out how to generate an expression":; };
        gFOR argument code={
            print "generate for":;
            lp  = argument[1];
            xp  = argument[2];
            lr  = argument["LoopRestrict"];
            st  = argument["StatemenT"];
            print ~"while" lp;
            if lr
                if lr == "attributes";  print,_"= " xp ".nextAttribute(" lp ")";
                or lr == "members";     print,_"= " xp ".nextMember(" lp ")";
            else
                print,_"= " xp ".next(" lp ")";
                if lr   print ~+"if (" lr ")",+:;
            runGenerated(st);
            print ,-; };
        gIF argument code={
            print `"gIF: tag=" argument.taG "text=" argument.texT:;
            dumpContents(argument);
            xp  := argument["ExpressioN"];
            xp  = unWrap(xp);
            st  := argument[2];
            el  := argument[3];
            endLabel = new("bcLabel");
            dumpContents(xp);
            gXpress(xp);
            if el.listLengtH;
                elseLabel = new("bcLabel");
                dst := elseLabel;
            else
                dst := endLabel;
            emitBC(bcBRZ +% dst);
            // then-branch: descend to the generated revisedList (st is a non-isGROUP
            // StatemenT whose expression hangs off as an attribute, so unWrap can't
            // reach it) and emit directly, same as the condition; fall back to
            // runGenerated for compound (block/nested) then-branches.
            stXP := st["revisedList"];
            if stXP.listLengtH;  gXpress(stXP);
            else    runGenerated(st);
            if el.listLengtH;
                dst := endLabel;
                emitBC(bcBR +% dst);
                emitBC(elseLabel);
                runGenerated(el);
            emitBC(endLabel);
            print `"End of gIF":;
            };
        gPrinT argument code={
            print `"Need to work out how to generate print statement":; };
        gWhilE argument code={
            xp  = argument[1];
            st  = argument[2];
            print ~,"while(" xp ")":+;
            runGenerated(st);
            print ,-; };
        gXpress argument code={
            tmp = unWrap(argument);
            for child in tmp; members
                nextChild = child.nexT;
                if child.isOperatoR;
                    if child.taG != "=";        emitBC(child);
                or child.registrY == "bcOPs";   emitBC(child);
                or child.isLiteraL;             emitBC(bcPushLit=child);
                else  emitBC(bcPushField +% child);
            };
        emitBC argument code={
            :generator bcLIST;
            bcLIST += argument;
            print `"emit tag=" argument.taG "content=" argument:;
            };
        /***********************************************************************
            Debugging action. Walks a bcLIST and prints each entry's tag and
            value. Use after emit-phase to verify what landed in the accumulator.
        ***********************************************************************/
        dumpBC argument code={
            print `"dumpBC for" argument.taG ":":;
            if argument.listLengtH;
                for grup in argument;
                    print ``"  tag=" grup.taG " op=" grup:;
            else print ``"single field xp":;
            };
        generatE argument code={
            print :"About to generate":;
            dumpContents(argument);
            for field in argument;
                runGenerated(field);
            print "End of generatE":;
        };
